>n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with their schools, they are no longer decision makers with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in schools. They have no voice. Mothers had been able to vote on school Boards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> since 1870</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The 2010 Academies Act saw that end. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ofsted’s inspections</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have become</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">narrow and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">data driven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t only things that are easy to measure are given merit. Ho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">you</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> measure a smile?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We cannot; y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">et a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ll parents want their children to smile.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Parents speak of not recognising the s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chool which Ofsted writes about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as the school that their children attend. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of course, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that within the community school m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">odel p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arents can also feel disen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">franchised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but within the L.A. there are  strong systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> independent of school management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provide a fair and transparent process for grievances to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">addressed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Within the academy and free school model, parents must make any appeal to the governors, who are appointed by the Foundation.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have included</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">examples of testimony</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from pare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all over England </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in order that you might understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> just how d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isempowered and unconnected many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> parents are feeling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">From a pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">at a forced academy in Surrey</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Forced Academy Process led to a downward spiral for our school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would wish to say that Roke Primary School was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a failing school in the eyes of the parents when the DfE first swept in. However, the whole forced academy process, and the way that it has been handled in relation to Roke, has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">been seriously destabilising to our school and affected us all. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">So far the p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rocess has done much more harm than good. It has been handled in such a way as to alienate and demoralise people and jeopardise the stability of our children’s education. By the end of the 2013 summer term 44% of the entire school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">staff had left, including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> twelve out of seventeen teachers (82% of the teaching staff!). Parents are taking children away from the school they loved and the local community was unsettled and angry. The affect on us has been huge, in terms of distress, stress, time and effort tryin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g to make our voices heard and many sleepless nights. It has been heart-breaking to see our good school ripped apart and many of our inspiring and motivated teachers leave.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Throughout the process, it has been hugely demoralising and frustrating to feel tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t the DfE has been ‘imposing’ rather than ‘consulting’. There was no sense of democracy at all. The consultation was effectively a sham and a waste of taxpayers money. The DfE ignored the findings of the consultation that parents were against academisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Harris as sponsor. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our experience since takeover by the Harris Federation academy chain last September is dire, despite our every effort to try and embrace the change and new beginnings; our positivity was incredibly short lived. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is no longer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any home school partnership to speak of, parents are not allowed in the school building, our previously colourful primary school has blank walls and no children’s work in the corridor, it is a corporate and sterile atmosphere. Parents are no longer invited</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in to view the children’s work. The curriculum information that we receive is sketchy. All the good initiatives put in place by the last management have been immediately scrapped. The correspondence sent home from the Harris Federation and the Principal r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">outinely include grammatical and spelling mistakes. Year 3 children were given a literacy task downloaded from the internet which was wholly in American English. Year 5 children were given a grammar test in which even the title ‘grammer’ was misspelled and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there were a handful of other shocking grammatical and formatting mistakes. The Christmas fair was cancelled, this would have been the only opportunity parents would have to enter the school building and see our children’s working environment. There were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overzealous uniform inspections where year 1 girls’ pinafore dresses were unzipped to check they had the correct Harris logoed shirt underneath (a child protection issue!). The list goes on. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.33pt; padding-left:5.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are also deeply concerned that the school has deflated the na</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tional curriculum levels which they say our children have achieved. Across the school parents are saying the levels and targets that were sent home for their child are now far too easy but yet they are expected to make much more than a whole year’s progres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s by the summer. In fact in many cases the levels predicted by the summer are the levels that class teachers informed parents that the children were working for in early October! We are concerned that there may be a wholesale massaging of data to make the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">value added by the Harris Federation takeover look better than it really is. If this is true, to use our children in this way and to send children home with disappointing results which have been adjusted for the sake of data manipulation really is immoral.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We do not expect the Government to take our claims seriously since it would vindicate Harris as sponsor but forced academy sponsor. What we are saying as parents is that it is a data smokescreen which is being used to justify removing our school from loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l authority control where justification does not actually exist. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Homework this year under the Harris federation has been sent home unmarked and we get no feedback. Maths books are marked by the children themselves with no feedback or comments from the tea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chers. This is a marked drop from what happened last year under Roke. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the short time since Harris took over, already 3 teachers have departed mid-term and more are expected to leave before the end of the academic year. The school now has an alarming po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licy of asking people to leave with immediate effect after they hand in their resignation letter. The staff members are paid for their notice period but are not encouraged to be in school. This has a hugely detrimental effect on the children who experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their teachers and dinner ladies disappearing suddenly without enough time to say goodbye. It is also terrible for staff morale and a sense of appreciation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.67pt; padding-left:6.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Communication with parents is now appalling. There is no suggestions box. There has been no surve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y of parents. There should have been clear communication to the parents about the closure. There is no longer an open door policy. The head teacher has never properly introduced herself to parents. There is no staff list, so parents have no easy way of kno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wing the names of people on the staff team. The Harris complaints procedure is very complex and unwieldy. The Harris Federation never reply to complaints directed to them by email.  Newsletters mainly contain a list of rules and regulations, and dates. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re is no real news or warmth. There are adverts on the newsletter for commercial businesses such as financial advice companies. There are no longer home school books for every child. There are no longer sharing learning sessions for parents to talk to thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r children about the work that they are doing. There are no longer any class newsletters or any information about the current topics being studied. The parent-teacher meetings are no longer held in the privacy of the classrooms but at tables in the main ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ll and there is no opportunity to see the children’s work or books. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.67pt; padding-left:6.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There has been no communication at all from the school about their vision or any of the changes they have made. For example French is now taught by a specialist teacher but parents have n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ever been informed. There is a new drama studio but parents have not been told what has become of the old library which was really a strength of the school and children do not seem to be able to borrow books from school anymore and the younger children no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">longer bring home story books to share with their parents. Again things that were really strengths at Roke have been discontinued with no consultation or even notification of parents.  A new start time to school day was introduced without consultation. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re was no communication about the closure of the Children’s centre on the school site despite Harris promising that they would continue previous arrangement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is no longer an IT system for the children to use from home to do maths and literacy exercis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es and share their learning with the class. Previously we had Fronter which was provided by the local LEA. Parents have received no communication at all about this, so we are left completely in the dark about plans for a new system. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.67pt; padding-left:6.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">confidential way to contact the school governors, except by letter. Parents cannot email them directly and everything must go via the school office and is read by the office staff and senior staff. The names and contact details of the governing body have n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ot been circulated.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parents are made to feel like a nuisance at the school now. Many parents are fearful to complain or to even go in and speak to the receptionist because the atmosphere is so unwelcoming. There is no anonymous way to make complaints or su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ggestions. Parents are forced to do so in person or by email. When parents raise issues by email the response often completely ignores the questions or concerns raised. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The school is no longer working collaboratively with the PTA who are struggling to hol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d events on the school premises- for example this week the Christmas Fair was cancelled due to withdrawal of support by the Harris management at short notice. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the first and most obvious changes was that the Roke uniform was replaced by a new Harris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> uniform. They is only a single supplier and parents now have to provide multiple Harris branded items with no chance to shop around for the most economical deal. The uniform is poor quality and looks like it is made in a sweatshop (probably by other peopl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e’s children). Many of our children are wearing the flimsy Harris raincoat rather than a proper winter coat, probably because many parents cannot afford two different coats, and the Harris coat is only optional in cold weather. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Changing the uniform for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whole school is extraordinarily wasteful – Harris made no attempt to collect the uniform for charity or recycling. Parents simply had to throw it in bin or recycle box at home. Some of the uniform was brand new. It was left to parents to organise their own</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> collection for charity and some of the Roke uniform was sent to a school for street children in Kenya. The onus should have been on the academy chain to sort this out not parents. It goes against the Government’s supposed green agenda to through thousands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of good jumpers, shirts and cardigans into landfill sites. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Harris have removed specialist social and emotional support for special needs children without a statement, leaving many parents in tears. They also stopped providing specialist one to one suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t and now provide support in groups or in the main classroom. They brought in these changes without properly informing the parents involved. Special needs provision remains an ongoing area of frustration and concern for parents. These were parents who were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> very happy with the arrangement under the old Roke system and are now having to fight for their children’s provision on a daily basis. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31pt; padding-left:5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Harris operate a policy where they do not use qualified supply teachers to cover absent class teachers- instead cover i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s done by unqualified TAs. This is disruptive to the quality of children’s education particularly higher up the school.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There have been no new clubs introduced. The grounds are looking shabby and unkempt with far more weeds and stinging nettles than unde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r the previous administration. Parents were sold the idea of an academy on the basis that there would be more money available and many thought that this might mean a smarter school perhaps even with a swimming pool. The reality is that things have gone rap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">idly downhill in a short space of time and even if positive changes have been made, parents do not know about them because the school is not keeping us informed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">_______________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">From a Parent at a London Secondary Converter</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When considering secondary education for our son, we were very clear that we wanted him to go to a community school and opted for our new local secondary school which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">opened in 2010.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although the school has yet to run to full capacity and provide GCSE res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ults, it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by other parents whose children went there as providing good teaching, a broad curriculum, inclusivity and diversity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The school has an integrated autistic unit and despite being in the more affluent part of the borough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is very repr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esentative of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local community.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We were therefore very disappointed to learn that after two short years in operation, the school under the leadership of the Head Teacher was considering becoming an academy. Despite vehement opposition from many Gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rnors (the decision to start the academy process was won by one vote) and by opposition of many parents, the school became an academy earlier this year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.33pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since that time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have observed a number of changes in the day to day running of the school that cau</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me concern.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In respect of staffing in the school, there were a number of departures of experienced teaching staff that may have been coincidental to the change but this left teaching vacancies that were later filled by young cheaper teachers with less e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xperience.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The school now appears to have an abundance of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very young teachers but little older experienced staff.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The school is also placing unqualified teachers in positions that were previously filled by qualified staff. My son's Form Tutor, previously </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a qualified teacher is now a teaching assistant.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parents of children with autistic needs attending the school are very concerned that their children will be excluded from the main school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with the autistic unit becoming a separate school resulting in their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schooled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">outside of mainstream education.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> I expect further changes to the organisation of the school but nothing confirmed, only rumours at this stage.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We have considered moving our son to another school, one that is still in the family </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the local authority but have not taken that decision because of the current uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within school status.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We do however feel angry and undermined.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rhetoric of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expanding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">parental choice is laughable because the reality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for us is that with the con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">version of more schools to academy status,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">parental choices and influence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are being undermined. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">____________</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">__</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">From a parent at a forced academy in Staffordshire</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our Primary School was inspected under the new Ofsted framework November 2012 and put into </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Special Measures. We were devastated. At the end of May 2013, Lord Nash imposed the Academy Order and an IEB was imposed. Our head teacher resigned.</span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Apparently the preferred sponsor is REAch2. Many parents were against being forced to become an academy. We</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> felt there weren’t enough facts or information sharing. No one could tell us why becoming an academy was going to improve our school. We were given no choice of sponsor.</span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.33pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a meeting, we asked the DfE</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> why we couldn't have another choice. They refused to tell us which other sponsors had been considered or what would happen if we didn't choose REach2 as sponsor. The consultation process mainly took place over the summer holiday, so it was almost impossib</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le for the Parents Action Group to do anything.</span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The DfE had paid Artelia (French management consultancy) to conduct the consultation. When it came to consulting interested parties in the community, schools, councillors and MPs in neighbouring authorities w</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere consulted (the MP for Aldridge and Brownhills and councillors from Walsall), but surprisingly not the local stake holders or even our local MP. This is because our postcode is a Walsall postcode. Clearly Artelia had absolutely no local knowledge or the</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y would have realised their error.</span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Anyway, the DfE rep. stated in a meeting that despite any findings in the consultation, the Secretary of State and Lord Nash had the final decision.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-indent:36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our views don’t matter.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">__________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Parent from a Primary Academ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">y Converter, Cornwall</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My children’s school became an Academy in September 2011.  During the consultation process we were assured by the Headteacher and Chair of Governors that the ethos of the school would not change and that the school was only going down</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this route to enable them to have more power to spend money on the things that they deem important: teaching and learning.  Yet, within a short period of time things began to change.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The school uniform, an issue that was raised at the consultation meeting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, was completely changed. Pupils now having to wear button-up stiff collared shirts, expensive knitted jumpers, ties and kilts for the girls.  All of these cost an extortionate amount and are tricky for the younger children to change into/out of.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The que</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stion was also raised, by myself, during the consultation process about the administration team having enough time to manage the new business side of becoming an academy.  It was, at the time, reassuring to hear that they would not need to employ an extra </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">secretary.  However, within 6 months the secretary became the business manager and two extra, full time secretaries were taken on to work in the reception – at what cost?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-