nows are employed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Dinner Hall is now located across a busy road. Teaching assistants often cover supervisory roles without adequate classroom training; in some cases training was promised, but never happened. There is an unusually high turn over of staff; some leaving w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith less than a days notice. There is no clear and transparent communication to the parents.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.33pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When parental concerns are raised they are negated and not considered. On one occasion approximately 100 children were taken to a public park with only 4 members o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f staff, to me this beggars belief, it is just so dangerous. The local community feel totally alienated. When the Principal’s son was employed to take the annual school photographs, children were not allowed to have their photograph taken unless they were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wearing the newly introduced Boater, my child did not yet have a Boater so was not allowed a school photograph (she was not allowed to borrow one from a friend). </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The admission policy seems to have chan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ged. If your child attends the p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rivate ‘Wellingtons Nu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rsery’, which the Principal’s daughter runs, then you are guaranteed to get a place at the Academy. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My personal grievances with the Academy caused my daughter and myself so much stress, anxiety and upset, that I was forced to remove her from the school (a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t the Principal’s suggestion).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>